The President gave a brief speech at the Scottish Event Campus in Glasgow, Scotland, thanking everyone for signing a commitment to reduce methane emissions. He emphasized the importance of taking action in the next decade to meet long-term climate goals and highlighted the significance of reducing methane emissions, which contribute significantly to global warming. The President announced a commitment to collectively reduce methane by 30% by 2030, with over 80 countries signing on so far. He discussed the benefits of reducing methane emissions, such as improving health, food supply, and the economy. The President also outlined new rules and initiatives to reduce methane emissions in the United States, including working with farmers and ranchers to implement climate-smart agriculture practices. He emphasized that reducing methane emissions presents an opportunity for job creation and economic recovery. The President concluded by expressing the United States' willingness to collaborate with other countries and encouraging more nations to join in reducing methane emissions globally.